# No secrets in chat or commands

Never print, quote, or paste secrets from `.env`, host env files, PEM keys, passwords, tokens, connection strings, or cloud credentials into chat, commits, logs, or tool output.

## Rules

- Do not `cat`/`type`/`Get-Content` files that contain secrets into the conversation.
- Do not write shell commands that echo secret values (`echo $VAR`, `printenv`, `grep` lines that include values).
- When checking env: report only key name, status (`OK`/`EMPTY`/`PLACEHOLDER`), length, and non-sensitive metadata (e.g. `sslmode` present, PEM has BEGIN/END).
- Do not print DB hostnames, bucket names, access key IDs, or masked URLs in chat unless the user explicitly asks — prefer “TCP ok / DNS ok / len=N”.
- Prefer connectivity tests (TCP, HTTP status) over dumping config.
- JWT/PEM: confirm shape and length only — never dump key material.
- If a command might leak secrets in stdout, redirect/filter before the result reaches chat.

## Examples

```text
❌ Get-Content .env
❌ Select-String -Path .env -Pattern SECRET
✅ Report COOKIE_SECRET len=64 status=OK
✅ Test-NetConnection … -Port 6432 → TcpTestSucceeded=True
```
